And you showed that alpha--

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:18.260
again, the
fine-structure constant

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:27.700
comes a0 was the so-called
Compton wavelength

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:30.790
of the electron, with a bar.

00:08:30.790 --> 00:08:33.030
So it's h bar over mc.

00:08:39.770 --> 00:08:41.750
Remember, that the
Broglie wavelength

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:45.530
is h over the momentum.

00:08:45.530 --> 00:08:48.830
The Compton wavelength
this h over mc.

00:08:48.830 --> 00:08:53.510
And the Bard can wave
at the h bar over mc.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:57.230
And that's what alpha
times a zero is.

00:08:57.230 --> 00:09:02.400
And that quantity
is about 400 Fermi.

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:06.470
It's already much smaller
than the Bohr radius.

00:09:06.470 --> 00:09:11.780
It's smaller by 137
from the Bohr radius.

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:15.830
And then if you do
alpha squared a0,

00:09:15.830 --> 00:09:20.645
that actually was the
classical electron radius.

00:09:24.570 --> 00:09:27.630
So you must divide
this by 137, again,

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:31.410
and it gives you
about 2.8 Fermi.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:35.520
And what you can remember
is that the size of a proton

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.560
is about a Fermi.

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:40.200
So that gives you a
little bit of intuition.

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:44.460
So those are the basic
numbers that we begin with,

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:46.055
with the hydrogen atom.

00:09:46.055 --> 00:09:52.140
It gives you a scale of what's
going on, the size of an atom,

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:55.640
and the energies that
we're supposed to get.

